to that question, so we should each take it, yeah.

239
00:12:55,590 --> 00:12:56,250
Yeah, I mean, I think.

240
00:12:57,435 --> 00:13:02,617
I think there are opportunities on Kickstarter, but I was looking over Kickstarter earlier

241
00:13:02,657 --> 00:13:07,819
this week about what's available right now, and I am constantly looking at what's on Kickstarter.

242
00:13:08,219 --> 00:13:12,680
And it does feel like the games that are successful are people who are not first-time creators.

243
00:13:12,880 --> 00:13:17,461
So it does seem like it's very, you know, unless you have something that really stands

244
00:13:17,602 --> 00:13:19,302
out, it's very difficult to...

245
00:13:19,983 --> 00:13:24,554
get started. It's better than probably digital games I would say still

246
00:13:24,995 --> 00:13:28,804
to be able to get in. The barrier to entry is okay but it's not easy.

247
00:13:31,474 --> 00:13:38,879
So when I started my business I had been a product developer and a product designer and I started my company with the express purpose of product design.

248
00:13:39,639 --> 00:13:45,943
I'd done product development, I know how important safety, packaging, advertising, shipping, all of it is.

249
00:13:46,564 --> 00:13:51,747
And I knew that that's an expertise that wasn't what I wanted to have, I wanted to focus on the design part.

250
00:13:52,207 --> 00:13:55,330
And I really, I didn't have the opportunity for Kickstarter when I started.

251
00:13:56,350 --> 00:13:59,953
But I wouldn't have gone that route anyway because I really like having a partner.

252
00:14:00,453 --> 00:14:03,654
who has that expertise and takes over that part of the job.

253
00:14:04,815 --> 00:14:09,757
Angie Holmstrom is the wholesale manager for Mindware

254
00:14:09,877 --> 00:14:11,657
and she sells Quirkle all over the world

255
00:14:12,278 --> 00:14:13,478
so much better than I can.

256
00:14:14,139 --> 00:14:16,860
And I'm so glad that I have a team doing all of that

257
00:14:16,980 --> 00:14:19,701
and working on my behalf on the game all the time

258
00:14:19,741 --> 00:14:21,161
when I'm working on the next game.

259
00:14:23,123 --> 00:14:28,907
So for me, having a publisher and having the eyes of a publisher and the polish of a publisher

260
00:14:29,467 --> 00:14:32,850
and the expertise of a publisher is my preference as a designer,

261
00:14:32,990 --> 00:14:39,755
but I recognize the financial incentive for Kickstarter can work much better for designers,

262
00:14:40,235 --> 00:14:43,518
and if you're willing to put in the extra work that Kickstarter requires,

263
00:14:44,418 --> 00:14:48,981
you can really maintain control of your game in a way that you might not necessarily be able to with a publisher.

264
00:14:50,177 --> 00:14:52,398
Can I just say though, like on the Kickstarter front,

265
00:14:52,678 --> 00:14:54,519
I feel like you can't ever get enough money

266
00:14:54,579 --> 00:14:57,501
to be able to make it, to be able to pay yourself at all.

267
00:14:57,521 --> 00:14:59,742
You can get enough money to make a product.

268
00:14:59,802 --> 00:15:02,144
Like if all you're doing is trying to get your dream

269
00:15:02,184 --> 00:15:03,725
out there, Kickstarter will do that.

270
00:15:03,765 --> 00:15:06,266
But like, I think like having the other person

271
00:15:06,306 --> 00:15:07,867
to look after a bunch of stuff,

272
00:15:08,067 --> 00:15:10,348
it really takes a lot of time to do all of that.

273
00:15:10,809 --> 00:15:15,272
And the nice part of having the publisher is I designed Quirkle in 2006.

274
00:15:15,612 --> 00:15:20,475
I'm continuing to design Quirkle spin-offs and expansions because that's what I've been asked for.

275
00:15:20,955 --> 00:15:28,440
But I'm not... they're continuing to work on it and grow it and I can spend my time on other things.

276
00:15:28,521 --> 00:15:34,565
So it's really nice having other people invested in the growth of something you're working on

277
00:15:34,945 --> 00:15:38,087
and you can move on to the next design project. I really appreciate that.

278
00:15:39,027 --> 00:15:43,072
Yeah, I feel like as a platform, Kickstarter has changed a lot over the years.

279
00:15:43,212 --> 00:15:47,436
It's become a little bit more, in some ways, much more stable.

280
00:15:47,636 --> 00:15:52,382
Like there are a lot more sort of orthodox ways of running a Kickstarter, which is both

281
00:15:52,422 --> 00:15:54,524
good and bad because there are all these rules that people follow.

282
00:15:54,584 --> 00:15:58,548
Like one of the fascinating things is like the rule of thumb is like launch your Kickstarter

283
00:15:58,588 --> 00:15:59,149
on a Tuesday.

284
00:16:00,230 --> 00:16:02,431
And that's like, that's the idea.

285
00:16:02,691 --> 00:16:04,312
But, but here's the thing, right?

286
00:16:04,933 --> 00:16:06,073
Everyone knows that, right?

287
00:16:06,113 --> 00:16:09,315
And so now every Tuesday, like 900 Kickstarters launch.

288
00:16:09,996 --> 00:16:10,676
And where's yours?

289
00:16:10,796 --> 00:16:11,577
It's in there, right?

290
00:16:11,637 --> 00:16:12,477
Like, it's in, it's,

291
00:16:12,978 --> 00:16:14,499
unless people are getting that in their feed,

292
00:16:14,579 --> 00:16:16,940
it's much, it's challenging for them to see it.

293
00:16:18,936 --> 00:16:24,983
And, you know, with all of these rules, with all these new setups where it's like play, you know, Kickstarter backers now demand, like,

294
00:16:25,243 --> 00:16:29,308
we want to see a gameplay video. We want to see reviews ahead of time. You should send it out to all these reviewers.

295
00:16:29,368 --> 00:16:33,533
We want to see, and which means you have to make prototypes for every reviewer before the game is done.

296
00:16:33,974 --> 00:16:38,239
We want to see how the game looks. We want to see near-final artwork on this Kickstarter, like.

297
00:16:38,739 --> 00:16:48,549
Used to be you could run a kick starter with like a couple of our pieces and a really good game idea and you know be really earnest right when I did the bargain quest kick starter originally.

298
00:16:49,290 --> 00:16:57,238
One of the piece of advice I got was like hey do the video yourself like do you have to have you know use your laptop camera or whatever and just sort of.

299
00:16:57,598 --> 00:16:59,259
talk about your game and what you're trying to do.

300
00:16:59,759 --> 00:17:02,060
And that really worked, that worked alright at the time.

301
00:17:02,481 --> 00:17:06,883
But these days, people want trailers for their board games,

302
00:17:07,003 --> 00:17:08,744
for them to do crazy money.

303
00:17:08,784 --> 00:17:11,025
They see a human face, like, who's this? What is this?

304
00:17:11,345 --> 00:17:12,706
This doesn't seem professional at all.

305
00:17:13,947 --> 00:17:16,008
Which is a weird expectation to have for Kickstarter,

306
00:17:16,028 --> 00:17:17,969
but it's one people are increasingly having.

307
00:17:18,169 --> 00:17:18,589
Yeah.

308
00:17:19,210 --> 00:17:22,833
and they're becoming a lot less tolerant of mistakes along that road as well.

309
00:17:22,853 --> 00:17:24,855
If you, you know, they're like,

310
00:17:25,435 --> 00:17:26,956
all these Kickstarters have already happened,

311
00:17:27,096 --> 00:17:31,620
and clearly we expect you to operate as good as the best Kickstarter.

312
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:36,044
And I would say, I mean, first of all, that doesn't sound like the work of a single person anymore.

313
00:17:36,544 --> 00:17:40,686
And secondly, I mean, what was it Simon said, was it the end of last year?

314
00:17:41,247 --> 00:17:46,289
I mean, they've had apparently all this Kickstarter success, but maybe the profits aren't quite there

315
00:17:46,369 --> 00:17:50,571
because they are investing so much money in this marketing and making what they are.

316
00:17:51,812 --> 00:17:56,154
The creator of Scythe posted like a really wonderful series of articles about,

317
00:17:56,214 --> 00:17:59,496
like you can look at the Stonemaier Games website, but they posted a series of articles about like...

318
00:18:00,394 --> 00:18:02,976
why I don't put my games on Kickstarter anymore, right?

319
00:18:03,016 --> 00:18:05,357
Like, why the platform no longer works for my model.

320
00:18:05,677 --> 00:18:07,058
But they also posted a series that were like,

321
00:18:07,338 --> 00:18:08,559
but if I did make a Kickstarter,

322
00:18:08,839 --> 00:18:09,880
here's how I would do it now.

323
00:18:10,400 --> 00:18:11,721
And they were, and then by the end of it,

324
00:18:11,741 --> 00:18:13,121
they were like, okay, maybe we'll do another one

325
00:18:13,141 --> 00:18:14,862
because they have, but you know,

326
00:18:14,882 --> 00:18:16,483
they have to play the game super differently.

327
00:18:17,202 --> 00:18:21,064
And it's a really intimidating prospect for new designers, but I mean, I wouldn't necessarily

328
00:18:21,124 --> 00:18:26,927
say don't go for it, but there are community expectations that like might need to be researched

329
00:18:27,548 --> 00:18:29,769
and you need to set your expectations, right?

330
00:18:29,789 --> 00:18:35,012
Like you can't expect to make Gloomhaven money every time, you know?

331
00:18:35,352 --> 00:18:39,735
But fans will expect you to deliver Gloomhaven quality correspondence and Gloomhaven quality

332
00:18:40,095 --> 00:18:45,078
like graphic design or what have you like a lot and it can be intimidating.

333
00:18:46,568 --> 00:18:47,910
being that available to fans.

334
00:18:47,970 --> 00:18:49,331
There was a really good talk earlier today

335
00:18:49,371 --> 00:18:50,712
by the people who made Dream Daddy

336
00:18:50,993 --> 00:18:53,655
about being constantly available,

337
00:18:53,675 --> 00:18:55,758
which is a thing people don't think about about Kickstarter.

338
00:18:56,198 --> 00:18:57,319
Sorry, I'm starting to ramble a bit.

339
00:18:57,780 --> 00:18:59,722
But when you run a Kickstarter,

340
00:19:00,022 --> 00:19:02,584
you are also on the hook to correspond

341
00:19:02,604 --> 00:19:05,127
with every commenter, every single person

342
00:19:05,147 --> 00:19:06,969
who has an idea about your game

343
00:19:06,989 --> 00:19:08,270
or has an opinion about your game.

344
00:19:09,168 --> 00:19:16,093
And if you go quiet for like more than 48 hours during a Kickstarter, people start to ask questions and get upset.

345
00:19:16,553 --> 00:19:17,914
And that is stressful.

346
00:19:18,234 --> 00:19:24,839
Generally, if you manage social media for a popular brand, or what becomes a popular brand, which isn't always even in your control.

347
00:19:25,479 --> 00:19:30,783
Based on this then, I mean, I would like to ask all the panel, how did you personally start?

348
00:19:31,143 --> 00:19:32,884
Where did your initial success come from?

349
00:19:32,944 --> 00:19:34,886
And based on that, what advice do you have for...

350
00:19:35,466 --> 00:19:41,008
you know, future aspiring designers, how do they become a success now that everything is constantly changing?

351
00:19:44,829 --> 00:19:48,510
Okay, well, so, I mean, my start in the industry was incredibly orthodox, right?

352
00:19:48,550 --> 00:19:54,612
Like, I applied for Fantasy Flight Games' game design position for an associate game designer.

353
00:19:55,052 --> 00:19:58,533
And, you know, that application was very much, it felt like applying to college, right?

354
00:19:58,573 --> 00:20:00,354
It's like, here's, you know, an essay section, and here...

355
00:20:00,794 --> 00:20:02,455
like write the rules to rock, paper, scissors,

356
00:20:03,495 --> 00:20:05,775
that sort of stuff, and then standard interview,

357
00:20:05,835 --> 00:20:08,076
and then I was in a salaried game design position

358
00:20:08,116 --> 00:20:10,157
for a while, which is really not a job that exists.

359
00:20:10,617 --> 00:20:14,098
I mean, it does, but it's not one that is readily available.

360
00:20:14,238 --> 00:20:16,098
It is a hard job to find, and most companies

361
00:20:16,298 --> 00:20:18,979
don't keep game designers on staff in that way.

362
00:20:20,779 --> 00:20:24,320
From there, after I was at FFG for several years, and then I

363
00:20:25,324 --> 00:20:29,612
left to go independent, partly at the behest of Tim Fowers,

364
00:20:30,393 --> 00:20:34,300
who has had a lot of success with Kickstarter,

365
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:35,062
with a lot of these things.

366
00:20:37,373 --> 00:20:43,756
I think for any new designer, I think definitely reach out to creators that you know and that

367
00:20:43,796 --> 00:20:49,479
you like who have products similar to yours because the industry is still kind of young

368
00:20:49,599 --> 00:20:53,181
and it's still not like super, it's not so crazy.

369
00:20:53,261 --> 00:20:57,443
Like Tim is so excited when new designers want to talk to him and he will answer any

370
00:20:57,503 --> 00:20:58,324
question that you have.

371
00:20:59,244 --> 00:21:04,107
I mean same here, just feel free to reach out to me on Twitter or whatever, but like most designers that you know

372
00:21:05,668 --> 00:21:10,771
will be thrilled to talk about how they're doing and like give you advice and give you suggestions about what's

373
00:21:11,532 --> 00:21:13,253
You know what worked for them

374
00:21:14,414 --> 00:21:17,536
Because we want this industry to grow and want you know kind of to see

375
00:21:19,377 --> 00:21:21,758
One of the big things though is that we are not always publishers.

376
00:21:21,778 --> 00:21:22,979
I get a lot of people who message me and say,

377
00:21:23,019 --> 00:21:25,381
hey, I have this game idea and I'm like, I'm not a publisher.

378
00:21:26,482 --> 00:21:28,423
That sounds like a great idea, but like, or like,

379
00:21:28,563 --> 00:21:33,967
I probably shouldn't look at it legally, but like, don't do that, right?

380
00:21:34,047 --> 00:21:36,649
But you can reach out for advice on like, you know,

381
00:21:36,669 --> 00:21:38,410
so what did you do when you were running your Kickstarter?

382
00:21:38,851 --> 00:21:40,292
Are there any things I might want to avoid?

383
00:21:40,392 --> 00:21:42,433
And some of them will be too busy to answer you,

384
00:21:42,453 --> 00:21:45,796
but some of them will be thrilled to, you know, to talk and to...

385
00:21:46,697 --> 00:21:49,019
give you advice of like pitfalls to avoid.

386
00:21:49,259 --> 00:21:53,743
So, based on that, would you recommend the orthodox approach if you apply to a large company

387
00:21:53,943 --> 00:21:55,764
and sort of cut your teeth there?

388
00:21:55,785 --> 00:21:58,006
Uh, I...

389
00:21:59,147 --> 00:22:01,549
For me, I was very privileged. I was in a...

390
00:22:01,789 --> 00:22:06,133
I had some amount of savings saved up that I was able to say, move to Minnesota from California,

391
00:22:06,873 --> 00:22:08,274
which is not something everyone could have done.

392
00:22:08,875 --> 00:22:12,257
Also, I know at Fantasy Flight they also offer an internship

393
00:22:12,337 --> 00:22:14,219
and several of their employees were former interns.

394
00:22:14,599 --> 00:22:17,620
But that internship was not a paid internship.

395
00:22:18,720 --> 00:22:20,781
It was like they work very hard to,

396
00:22:20,901 --> 00:22:22,921
we work very hard to teach the interns

397
00:22:23,281 --> 00:22:25,202
and like to give them a valuable experience,

398
00:22:25,242 --> 00:22:27,002
but it's not a paid position.

399
00:22:27,762 --> 00:22:29,663
And so only the people who could do that

400
00:22:29,703 --> 00:22:31,403
were people who could afford to basically take

401
00:22:31,443 --> 00:22:35,584
like three months to just come into a studio every day

402
00:22:35,624 --> 00:22:36,824
and just kind of learn, right?

403
00:22:36,864 --> 00:22:38,325
Like it's almost like going to school.

404
00:22:39,045 --> 00:22:44,128
I think absolutely when you see these job openings, you can't lose anything by applying,

405
00:22:44,168 --> 00:22:47,569
and half of the applications are really good exercises.

406
00:22:47,589 --> 00:22:53,332
Write the rules to rock, paper, scissors coherently is a great thing to do.

407
00:22:53,633 --> 00:22:58,595
Even if I had never gotten the job, it helped me in my technical writing.

408
00:22:58,895 --> 00:23:01,937
So Susan, is that the best way to become a games designer?

409
00:23:03,073 --> 00:23:03,573
I have no idea.

410
00:23:07,678 --> 00:23:10,000
My own experience was I knew I wanted to create something

411
00:23:10,020 --> 00:23:11,922
and you were asking why be a game designer earlier

412
00:23:11,962 --> 00:23:14,205
and it's because you have to make something.

413
00:23:14,225 --> 00:23:16,527
You're just driven, you're compelled,

414
00:23:16,627 --> 00:23:17,588
you wake up in the middle of the night

415
00:23:17,608 --> 00:23:18,269
and you think about it.

416
00:23:18,730 --> 00:23:20,732
That's the reason you become a novelist

417
00:23:20,792 --> 00:23:22,854
or you design jewelry or wallpaper or anything.

418
00:23:22,874 --> 00:23:24,356
You're just compelled.

419
00:23:25,636 --> 00:23:33,360
And so I knew I wanted to design something but I didn't know what and I worked at a toy and game company and they gave me the opportunity to turn in ideas and I went a little overboard and turned in 200 ideas.

420
00:23:33,921 --> 00:23:37,802
And they said, okay, we're going to move you to the product development department and teach you how to do this.

421
00:23:38,783 --> 00:23:43,145
I was super lucky. I was at the toy and game company because I wanted to make something and they made things.

422
00:23:44,967 --> 00:23:48,911
And then when I started, they moved out of the area and I was looking for another job

423
00:23:48,971 --> 00:23:52,234
and I couldn't find anything I liked as much and my husband encouraged me to start my own

424
00:23:52,294 --> 00:23:52,674
company.

425
00:23:52,694 --> 00:23:58,840
I had the blessing and the privilege of having a partner who had a full-time job in insurance

426
00:23:58,900 --> 00:24:04,706
and I could start a company with the ability to fail and that was a great gift that not

427
00:24:04,746 --> 00:24:05,527
everybody has.

428
00:24:06,828 --> 00:24:11,531
But I started in toys and toys have in-house designers.

429
00:24:11,591 --> 00:24:13,312
Toy companies design things in-house.

430
00:24:13,332 --> 00:24:15,914
They're much less used to working with out-of-house designers.

431
00:24:16,294 --> 00:24:20,677
When I switched to games, I found game companies are much more open to working with out-of-house

432
00:24:20,717 --> 00:24:21,097
designers.

433
00:24:21,117 --> 00:24:21,978
That's their model.

434
00:24:22,518 --> 00:24:25,599
So they're much more approachable, they're much more willing to look at things,

435
00:24:26,019 --> 00:24:29,480
they're much more willing to work with people who don't have as much experience.

436
00:24:29,940 --> 00:24:33,381
So it's really, Kickstarter is one way to get in,

437
00:24:33,661 --> 00:24:37,922
but game companies are much more open than a lot of different industries are.

438
00:24:38,642 --> 00:24:42,283
And I think that's a really nice thing about it.

439
00:24:42,383 --> 00:24:43,903
And what you said is true also.

440
00:24:44,444 --> 00:24:47,464
I know many designers who are happy to answer emails

441
00:24:47,564 --> 00:24:49,325
and respond to requests about information.

442
00:24:49,845 --> 00:24:51,245
It's still a very friendly...

443
00:24:52,766 --> 00:24:58,409
friendly industry. And advice, as you're designing games, I try to remember this myself,

444
00:24:58,549 --> 00:25:04,392
write your instructions early and often. You can do yourself no harm by starting to write

445
00:25:04,412 --> 00:25:08,614
instructions as soon as you possibly can. Edit them, stay on top of them, keep them

446
00:25:08,674 --> 00:25:12,416
current with your current version of the game. It will just help in the end because instruction

447
00:25:12,456 --> 00:25:16,098
writing is one of the hardest parts of this job. And the sooner you start, the easier

448
00:25:16,118 --> 00:25:16,298
it is.

449
00:25:16,962 --> 00:25:19,963
Can I ask how do you get 200 ideas for games?

450
00:25:20,183 --> 00:25:21,243
I have like two.

451
00:25:21,283 --> 00:25:23,104
They weren't just games, it was toys and games.

452
00:25:23,564 --> 00:25:26,784
So it was 200 different products that I could see

453
00:25:26,824 --> 00:25:29,085
in this company's line and I was young.

454
00:25:30,005 --> 00:25:30,965
I didn't sleep for a month.

455
00:25:31,025 --> 00:25:34,006
I was so excited about having one of these

456
00:25:34,046 --> 00:25:35,366
become an actual product.

457
00:25:36,306 --> 00:25:38,727
I think of those 205 became actual products,

458
00:25:39,147 --> 00:25:40,827
which was not a bad ratio for someone

459
00:25:40,847 --> 00:25:42,228
who had no clue what they were doing.

460
00:25:43,109 --> 00:25:45,933
And I got to work on two of them and turn them into products.

461
00:25:45,973 --> 00:25:47,996
And when you get to hold them in your hand,

462
00:25:48,036 --> 00:25:49,398
you're like, I made this.

463
00:25:49,839 --> 00:25:50,720
It's really exciting.

464
00:25:51,181 --> 00:25:52,522
So Jen, is that the secret?

465
00:25:52,563 --> 00:25:53,003
Don't sleep.

466
00:25:54,793 --> 00:26:00,118
